    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.8.0-dev+15-g245858460\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nn/a\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nst\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nst-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nrepo\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nsee below\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe 'breakindentopt' option should have mapping semantics.\r\n\r\n--When-\r\nvim.opt.breakindentopt = {sbr = true, shift = 3}\r\n--Then-\r\nvim.opt.breakindentopt:get() \r\n--should return the table with mappings, but returns {}\r\n\r\n\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nvim.cmd [[set breakindentopt=sbr,shift:3]]\r\nvim.opt.breakindentopt:get() == {\"sbr\", \"shift:3\"}",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "This should get a bit more priority...\r\n\r\nMaking this kind of behaviour more consistent between options like `vim.opt.listchars` and `vim.opt.breakindentopt` seems like it would be an easy way of subtly making it easier to understand the process of using lua for your config and easily transitioning from vimscript.\r\n\r\nAs the original issue describes setting the value directly does not work and neither does `vim.opt.breakindentopt:append(...)`. I don't know what is happening behind the scenes, but this seems a bit weird since this option seems to be stored as a table anyways.",
